fields.name: stopsByRadius
fields.description:
Get all stops within the specified radius from a location. The returned type
is a Relay connection (see
https://facebook.github.io/relay/graphql/connections.htm). The stopAtDistance
type has two values: stop and distance.

args.name: lat
args.description: Latitude of the location (WGS 84)

args.name: lon
args.description: Longitude of the location (WGS 84)

args.name: radius
args.description:
Radius (in meters) to search for from the specified location. Note that this
is walking distance along streets and paths rather than a geographic distance.

args.name: agency
args.description: Deprecated, use argument `feeds` instead

args.name: feeds
args.description: List of feed ids from which stops are returned

fields.name: nearest
fields.description:
Get all places (stops, stations, etc. with coordinates) within the specified
radius from a location. The returned type is a Relay connection (see
https://facebook.github.io/relay/graphql/connections.htm). The placeAtDistance
type has two fields: place and distance. The search is done by walking so the
distance is according to the network of walkable streets and paths.

args.name: lat
args.description: Latitude of the location (WGS 84)

args.name: lon
args.description: Longitude of the location (WGS 84)

args.name: maxDistance
args.description:
Maximum distance (in meters) to search for from the specified location. Note
that this is walking distance along streets and paths rather than a
geographic distance. Default is 2000m

args.name: maxResults
args.description: Maximum number of results. Search is stopped when this limit is reached. Default is 20.

args.name: filterByPlaceTypes
args.description: Only return places that are one of these types, e.g. `STOP` or `BICYCLE_RENT`

args.name: filterByModes
args.description:
Only return places that are related to one of these transport modes. This
argument can be used to return e.g. only nearest railway stations or only
nearest places related to bicycling.

args.name: filterByIds
args.description: Only include places that match one of the given GTFS ids.

fields.name: plan
fields.description: Plans an itinerary from point A to point B based on the given arguments

args.name: date
args.description: Date of departure or arrival in format YYYY-MM-DD. Default value: current date

args.name: time
args.description: Time of departure or arrival in format hh:mm:ss. Default value: current time

args.name: from
args.description:
The geographical location where the itinerary begins.  
 Use either this argument or `fromPlace`, but not both.

args.name: to
args.description:
The geographical location where the itinerary ends.  
 Use either this argument or `toPlace`, but not both.

args.name: fromPlace
args.description:
The place where the itinerary begins in format `name::place`, where `place`
is either a lat,lng pair (e.g. `Pasila::60.199041,24.932928`) or a stop id
(e.g. `Pasila::HSL:1000202`).  
 Use either this argument or `from`, but not both.

args.name: toPlace
args.description:
The place where the itinerary ends in format `name::place`, where `place` is
either a lat,lng pair (e.g. `Pasila::60.199041,24.932928`) or a stop id
(e.g. `Pasila::HSL:1000202`).  
 Use either this argument or `to`, but not both.

args.name: wheelchair
args.description: Whether the itinerary must be wheelchair accessible. Default value: false

args.name: numItineraries
args.description: The maximum number of itineraries to return. Default value: 3.

args.name: maxWalkDistance
args.description:
The maximum distance (in meters) the user is willing to walk per walking
section. If the only transport mode allowed is `WALK`, then the value of
this argument is ignored.  
 Default: 2000m  
 Maximum value: 15000m  
 **Note:** If this argument has a relatively small value and only some
transport modes are allowed (e.g. `WALK` and `RAIL`), it is possible to get
an itinerary which has (useless) back and forth public transport legs to
avoid walking too long distances.

args.name: maxPreTransitTime
args.description:
The maximum time (in seconds) of pre-transit travel when using
drive-to-transit (park and ride or kiss and ride). Default value: 1800.

args.name: maxSlope
args.description:
The maximum slope, up or downhill, that can be used in wheelchair accessible
routing. Value is between 0 and 1, and calculated by dividing change of
elevation by change of distance. Default value: 0.0833333333333

args.name: carParkCarLegWeight
args.description:
How expensive it is to drive a car when car&parking, increase this value to
make car driving legs shorter. Default value: 1.

args.name: itineraryFiltering
args.description:
How easily bad itineraries are filtered from results. Value 0 (default)
disables filtering. Itineraries are filtered if they are worse than another
one in some respect (e.g. more walking) by more than the percentage of
filtering level, which is calculated by dividing 100% by the value of this
argument (e.g. `itineraryFiltering = 0.5`  200% worse itineraries are filtered).

args.name: walkReluctance
args.description:
A multiplier for how bad walking is, compared to being in transit for equal
lengths of time.Empirically, values between 10 and 20 seem to correspond
well to the concept of not wanting to walk too much without asking for
totally ridiculous itineraries, but this observation should in no way be
taken as scientific or definitive. Your mileage may vary. Default value: 2.0

args.name: walkOnStreetReluctance
args.description: How much more reluctant is the user to walk on streets with car traffic allowed. Default value: 1.0

args.name: waitReluctance
args.description:
How much worse is waiting for a transit vehicle than being on a transit
vehicle, as a multiplier. The default value treats wait and on-vehicle time
as the same. It may be tempting to set this higher than walkReluctance (as
studies often find this kind of preferences among riders) but the planner
will take this literally and walk down a transit line to avoid waiting at a
stop. This used to be set less than 1 (0.95) which would make waiting
offboard preferable to waiting onboard in an interlined trip. That is also
undesirable. If we only tried the shortest possible transfer at each stop to
neighboring stop patterns, this problem could disappear. Default value: 1.0.

args.name: waitAtBeginningFactor
args.description:
How much less bad is waiting at the beginning of the trip (replaces
`waitReluctance` on the first boarding). Default value: 0.4

args.name: walkSpeed
args.description: Max walk speed along streets, in meters per second. Default value: 1.33

args.name: bikeSpeed
args.description: Max bike speed along streets, in meters per second. Default value: 5.0

args.name: bikeSwitchTime
args.description: Time to get on and off your own bike, in seconds. Default value: 0

args.name: bikeSwitchCost
args.description: Cost of getting on and off your own bike. Unit: seconds. Default value: 0

args.name: optimize
args.description: Optimization type for bicycling legs, e.g. prefer flat terrain. Default value: `QUICK`

args.name: triangle
args.description: Triangle optimization parameters for bicycling legs. Only effective when `optimize` is set to **TRIANGLE**.

args.name: arriveBy
args.description:
Whether the itinerary should depart at the specified time (false), or arrive
to the destination at the specified time (true). Default value: false.

args.name: intermediatePlaces
args.description: An ordered list of intermediate locations to be visited.

args.name: preferred
args.description: List of routes and agencies which are given higher preference when planning the itinerary

args.name: unpreferred
args.description: List of routes and agencies which are given lower preference when planning the itinerary

args.name: walkBoardCost
args.description: This prevents unnecessary transfers by adding a cost for boarding a vehicle. Unit: seconds. Default value: 600

args.name: bikeBoardCost
args.description:
Separate cost for boarding a vehicle with a bicycle, which is more difficult
than on foot. Unit: seconds. Default value: 600

args.name: banned
args.description: List of routes, trips, agencies and stops which are not used in the itinerary

args.name: transferPenalty
args.description:
An extra penalty added on transfers (i.e. all boardings except the first
one). Not to be confused with bikeBoardCost and walkBoardCost, which are the
cost of boarding a vehicle with and without a bicycle. The boardCosts are
used to model the 'usual' perceived cost of using a transit vehicle, and the
transferPenalty is used when a user requests even less transfers. In the
latter case, we don't actually optimize for fewest transfers, as this can
lead to absurd results. Consider a trip in New York from Grand Army Plaza
(the one in Brooklyn) to Kalustyan's at noon. The true lowest transfers
route is to wait until midnight, when the 4 train runs local the whole way.
The actual fastest route is the 2/3 to the 4/5 at Nevins to the 6 at Union
Square, which takes half an hour. Even someone optimizing for fewest
transfers doesn't want to wait until midnight. Maybe they would be willing
to walk to 7th Ave and take the Q to Union Square, then transfer to the 6.
If this takes less than optimize_transfer_penalty seconds, then that's what
we'll return. Default value: 0.

args.name: batch
args.description:
This argument has no use for itinerary planning and will be removed later.  
 ~~When true, do not use goal direction or stop at the target, build a full SPT. Default value: false.~~

args.name: modes
args.description:
Deprecated, use `transportModes` instead.  
 ~~The set of TraverseModes that a user is willing to use. Default value: WALK | TRANSIT.~~

args.name: transportModes
args.description: List of transportation modes that the user is willing to use. Default: `["WALK","TRANSIT"]`

args.name: modeWeight
args.description: The weight multipliers for transit modes. WALK, BICYCLE, CAR, TRANSIT and LEG_SWITCH are not included.

args.name: allowBikeRental
args.description: Is bike rental allowed? Default value: false

args.name: boardSlack
args.description: Invariant: `boardSlack + alightSlack <= transferSlack`. Default value: 0

args.name: alightSlack
args.description: Invariant: `boardSlack + alightSlack <= transferSlack`. Default value: 0

args.name: minTransferTime
args.description:
A global minimum transfer time (in seconds) that specifies the minimum
amount of time that must pass between exiting one transit vehicle and
boarding another. This time is in addition to time it might take to walk
between transit stops. Default value: 0

args.name: nonpreferredTransferPenalty
args.description: Penalty (in seconds) for using a non-preferred transfer. Default value: 180

args.name: maxTransfers
args.description: Maximum number of transfers. Default value: 2

args.name: startTransitStopId
args.description:
This argument has currently no effect on which itineraries are returned. Use
argument `fromPlace` to start the itinerary from a specific stop.  
 ~~A transit stop that this trip must start from~~

args.name: startTransitTripId
args.description:
ID of the trip on which the itinerary starts. This argument can be used to
plan itineraries when the user is already onboard a vehicle. When using this
argument, arguments `time` and `from` should be set based on a vehicle
position message received from the vehicle running the specified trip.  
 **Note:** this argument only takes into account the route and estimated
travel time of the trip (and therefore arguments `time` and `from` must be
used correctly to get meaningful itineraries).

args.name: claimInitialWait
args.description:
No effect on itinerary planning, adjust argument `time` instead to get later departures.  
 ~~The maximum wait time in seconds the user is willing to delay trip start. Only effective in Analyst.~~

args.name: reverseOptimizeOnTheFly
args.description:
**Consider this argument experimental**  setting this argument to true
causes timeouts and unoptimal routes in many cases.  
 When true, reverse optimize (find alternative transportation mode, which
still arrives to the destination in time) this search on the fly after
processing each transit leg, rather than reverse-optimizing the entire path
when it's done. Default value: false.

args.name: omitCanceled
args.description: When false, return itineraries using canceled trips. Default value: true.

args.name: ignoreRealtimeUpdates
args.description: When true, realtime updates are ignored during this search. Default value: false

args.name: disableRemainingWeightHeuristic
args.description:
Only useful for testing and troubleshooting.  
 ~~If true, the remaining weight heuristic is disabled. Currently only
implemented for the long distance path service. Default value: false.~~

args.name: locale
args.description:
Two-letter language code (ISO 639-1) used for returned text.  
 **Note:** only part of the data has translations available and names of
stops and POIs are returned in their default language. Due to missing
translations, it is sometimes possible that returned text uses a mixture of two languages.

args.name: ticketTypes
args.description:
**Deprecated:** Use `allowedTicketTypes` instead.  
A comma-separated list of allowed ticket types.

args.name: allowedTicketTypes
args.description:
List of ticket types that are allowed to be used in itineraries.  
See `ticketTypes` query for list of possible ticket types.

args.name: heuristicStepsPerMainStep
args.description: Tuning parameter for the search algorithm, mainly useful for testing.

args.name: compactLegsByReversedSearch
args.description:
Whether legs should be compacted by performing a reversed search.  
 **Experimental argument, will be removed!**

args.name: allowedBikeRentalNetworks
args.description: Which bike rental networks can be used. By default, all networks are allowed.

types.name: ID
types.description: The `ID` scalar type represents a unique identifier, often used to refetch an object or as key for a cache. The ID type appears in a JSON response as a String; however, it is not intended to be human-readable. When expected as an input type, any string (such as `"4"`) or integer (such as `4`) input value will be accepted as an ID.

types.name: Node
types.description: An object with an ID

fields.name: id
fields.description: The ID of an object

types.description: A feed provides routing data (stops, routes, timetables, etc.) from one or more public transport agencies.

fields.name: feedId
fields.description: ID of the feed

fields.name: agencies
fields.description: List of agencies which provide data to this feed

types.name: String
types.description: The `String` scalar type represents textual data, represented as UTF-8 character sequences. The String type is most often used by GraphQL to represent free-form human-readable text.

types.name: Agency
types.description: A public transport agency

fields.name: id
fields.description: Global object ID provided by Relay. This value can be used to refetch this object using **node** query.

fields.name: gtfsId
fields.description: Agency feed and id

fields.name: name
fields.description: Name of the agency

fields.name: url
fields.description: URL to the home page of the agency

fields.name: timezone
fields.description: ID of the time zone which this agency operates on

fields.name: phone

fields.name: fareUrl

types.name: Route
types.description:
Route represents a public transportation service, usually from point A to point
B and *back*, shown to customers under a single name, e.g. bus 550. Routes
contain patterns (see field `patterns`), which describe different variants of
the route, e.g. outbound pattern from point A to point B and inbound pattern
from point B to point A.

fields.name: id
fields.description: Global object ID provided by Relay. This value can be used to refetch this object using **node** query.

fields.name: gtfsId
fields.description: ID of the route in format `FeedId:RouteId`

fields.name: agency
fields.description: Agency operating the route

fields.name: shortName
fields.description: Short name of the route, usually a line number, e.g. 550

fields.name: longName
fields.description: Long name of the route, e.g. Helsinki-Leppvaara

fields.name: mode
fields.description: Transport mode of this route, e.g. `BUS`

fields.name: type
fields.description:
The raw GTFS route type as a integer. For the list of possible values, see:
https://developers.google.com/transit/gtfs/reference/#routestxt and
https://developers.google.com/transit/gtfs/reference/extended-route-types

fields.name: color
fields.description:
The color (in hexadecimal format) the agency operating this route would prefer
to use on UI elements (e.g. polylines on a map) related to this route. This
value is not available for most routes.

fields.name: textColor
fields.description:
The color (in hexadecimal format) the agency operating this route would prefer
to use when displaying text related to this route. This value is not available
for most routes.

fields.name: patterns
fields.description: List of patterns which operate on this route

fields.name: stops
fields.description: List of stops on this route

fields.name: trips
fields.description: List of trips which operate on this route

fields.name: alerts
fields.description: List of alerts which have an effect on the route

enumValues.name: LEG_SWITCH
enumValues.description: Only used internally. No use for API users.

enumValues.name: TRANSIT
enumValues.description: A special transport mode, which includes all public transport.

types.name: Int
types.description: The `Int` scalar type represents non-fractional signed whole numeric values. Int can represent values between -(2^31) and 2^31 - 1.

enumValues.name: NO_INFORMATION
enumValues.description: There is no bike information for the trip.

enumValues.name: ALLOWED
enumValues.description: The vehicle being used on this particular trip can accommodate at least one bicycle.

enumValues.name: NOT_ALLOWED
enumValues.description: No bicycles are allowed on this trip.

types.name: Pattern
types.description:
Pattern is sequence of stops used by trips on a specific direction and variant
of a route. Most routes have only two patterns: one for outbound trips and one
for inbound trips

fields.name: id
fields.description: Global object ID provided by Relay. This value can be used to refetch this object using **node** query.

fields.name: route
fields.description: The route this pattern runs on

fields.name: directionId
fields.description:
Direction of the pattern. Possible values: 0, 1 or -1.  
 -1 indicates that the direction is irrelevant, i.e. the route has patterns only in one direction.

fields.name: name
fields.description:
Name of the pattern. Pattern name can be just the name of the route or it can
include details of destination and origin stops.

fields.name: code
fields.description: ID of the pattern

fields.name: headsign
fields.description: Vehicle headsign used by trips of this pattern

fields.name: trips
fields.description: Trips which run on this pattern

fields.name: tripsForDate
fields.description: Trips which run on this pattern on the specified date

args.name: serviceDay
args.description: Deprecated, please switch to serviceDate instead

args.name: serviceDate
args.description: Return trips of the pattern active on this date. Format: YYYYMMDD

fields.name: stops
fields.description: List of stops served by this pattern

fields.name: patternGeometry
fields.description: Coordinates of the route of this pattern in Google polyline encoded format

fields.name: semanticHash
fields.description:
Hash code of the pattern. This value is stable and not dependent on the
pattern id, i.e. this value can be used to check whether two patterns are the
same, even if their ids have changed.

fields.name: alerts
fields.description: List of alerts which have an effect on trips of the pattern

types.name: Trip
types.description: Trip is a specific occurance of a pattern, usually identified by route, direction on the route and exact departure time.

fields.name: id
fields.description: Global object ID provided by Relay. This value can be used to refetch this object using **node** query.

fields.name: gtfsId
fields.description: ID of the trip in format `FeedId:TripId`

fields.name: route
fields.description: The route the trip is running on

fields.name: activeDates
fields.description: List of dates when this trip is in service. Format: YYYYMMDD

fields.name: tripHeadsign
fields.description: Headsign of the vehicle when running on this trip

fields.name: routeShortName
fields.description: Short name of the route this trip is running. See field `shortName` of Route.

fields.name: directionId
fields.description:
Direction code of the trip, i.e. is this the outbound or inbound trip of a
pattern. Possible values: 0, 1 or `null` if the direction is irrelevant, i.e.
the pattern has trips only in one direction.

fields.name: wheelchairAccessible
fields.description: Whether the vehicle running this trip can be boarded by a wheelchair

fields.name: bikesAllowed
fields.description: Whether bikes are allowed on board the vehicle running this trip

fields.name: pattern
fields.description: The pattern the trip is running on

fields.name: stops
fields.description: List of stops this trip passes through

fields.name: semanticHash
fields.description: Hash code of the trip. This value is stable and not dependent on the trip id.

fields.name: stoptimes
fields.description: List of times when this trip arrives to or departs from a stop

fields.name: departureStoptime
fields.description: Departure time from the first stop

args.name: serviceDate
args.description:
Date for which the departure time is returned. Format: YYYYMMDD. If this
argument is not used, field `serviceDay` in the stoptime will have a value of 0.

fields.name: arrivalStoptime
fields.description: Arrival time to the final stop

args.name: serviceDate

types.name: __Schema
types.description: A GraphQL Schema defines the capabilities of a GraphQL server. It exposes all available types and directives on the server, as well as the entry points for query, mutation, and subscription operations.

fields.name: types
fields.description: A list of all types supported by this server.

fields.name: queryType
fields.description: The type that query operations will be rooted at.

fields.name: mutationType
fields.description: If this server supports mutation, the type that mutation operations will be rooted at.

fields.name: subscriptionType
fields.description: If this server support subscription, the type that subscription operations will be rooted at.

fields.name: directives
fields.description: A list of all directives supported by this server.

types.name: __Type
types.description:
The fundamental unit of any GraphQL Schema is the type. There are many kinds of types in GraphQL as represented by the `__TypeKind` enum.

Depending on the kind of a type, certain fields describe information about that type. Scalar types provide no information beyond a name and description, while Enum types provide their values. Object and Interface types provide the fields they describe. Abstract types, Union and Interface, provide the Object types possible at runtime. List and NonNull types compose other types.

types.name: __TypeKind
types.description: An enum describing what kind of type a given `__Type` is.

enumValues.name: SCALAR
enumValues.description: Indicates this type is a scalar.

enumValues.name: OBJECT
enumValues.description: Indicates this type is an object. `fields` and `interfaces` are valid fields.

enumValues.name: INTERFACE
enumValues.description: Indicates this type is an interface. `fields` and `possibleTypes` are valid fields.

enumValues.name: UNION
enumValues.description: Indicates this type is a union. `possibleTypes` is a valid field.

enumValues.name: ENUM
enumValues.description: Indicates this type is an enum. `enumValues` is a valid field.

enumValues.name: INPUT_OBJECT
enumValues.description: Indicates this type is an input object. `inputFields` is a valid field.

enumValues.name: LIST
enumValues.description: Indicates this type is a list. `ofType` is a valid field.

enumValues.name: NON_NULL
enumValues.description: Indicates this type is a non-null. `ofType` is a valid field.

types.name: __Field
types.description: Object and Interface types are described by a list of Fields, each of which has a name, potentially a list of arguments, and a return type.

types.name: __InputValue
types.description: Arguments provided to Fields or Directives and the input fields of an InputObject are represented as Input Values which describe their type and optionally a default value.

fields.name: defaultValue
fields.description: A GraphQL-formatted string representing the default value for this input value.

types.name: __EnumValue
types.description: One possible value for a given Enum. Enum values are unique values, not a placeholder for a string or numeric value. However an Enum value is returned in a JSON response as a string.

types.name: __Directive
types.description:
A Directive provides a way to describe alternate runtime execution and type validation behavior in a GraphQL document.

In some cases, you need to provide options to alter GraphQL's execution behavior in ways field arguments will not suffice, such as conditionally including or skipping a field. Directives provide this by describing additional information to the executor.

types.name: __DirectiveLocation
types.description: A Directive can be adjacent to many parts of the GraphQL language, a __DirectiveLocation describes one such possible adjacencies.

enumValues.name: QUERY
enumValues.description: Location adjacent to a query operation.

enumValues.name: MUTATION
enumValues.description: Location adjacent to a mutation operation.

enumValues.name: SUBSCRIPTION
enumValues.description: Location adjacent to a subscription operation.

enumValues.name: FRAGMENT_DEFINITION
enumValues.description: Location adjacent to a fragment definition.

enumValues.name: FRAGMENT_SPREAD
enumValues.description: Location adjacent to a fragment spread.

enumValues.name: INLINE_FRAGMENT
enumValues.description: Location adjacent to an inline fragment.

enumValues.name: VARIABLE_DEFINITION
enumValues.description: Location adjacent to a variable definition.

enumValues.name: SCHEMA
enumValues.description: Location adjacent to a schema definition.

enumValues.name: SCALAR
enumValues.description: Location adjacent to a scalar definition.

enumValues.name: OBJECT
enumValues.description: Location adjacent to an object type definition.

enumValues.name: FIELD_DEFINITION
enumValues.description: Location adjacent to a field definition.

enumValues.name: ARGUMENT_DEFINITION
enumValues.description: Location adjacent to an argument definition.

enumValues.name: INTERFACE
enumValues.description: Location adjacent to an interface definition.

enumValues.name: UNION
enumValues.description: Location adjacent to a union definition.

enumValues.name: ENUM
enumValues.description: Location adjacent to an enum definition.

enumValues.name: ENUM_VALUE
enumValues.description: Location adjacent to an enum value definition.

enumValues.name: INPUT_OBJECT
enumValues.description: Location adjacent to an input object type definition.

enumValues.name: INPUT_FIELD_DEFINITION
enumValues.description: Location adjacent to an input object field definition.

directives.name: skip
directives.description: Directs the executor to skip this field or fragment when the `if` argument is true.

args.name: if
args.description: Skipped when true.

directives.name: include
directives.description: Directs the executor to include this field or fragment only when the `if` argument is true.

args.name: if
args.description: Included when true.

directives.name: deprecated
directives.description: Marks an element of a GraphQL schema as no longer supported.

args.name: reason
args.description: Explains why this element was deprecated, usually also including a suggestion for how to access supported similar data. Formatted using the Markdown syntax (as specified by [CommonMark](https://commonmark.org/).

directives.name: client
directives.description: Direct the client to resolve this field locally, either from the cache or local resolvers.

args.name: always
args.description:
When true, the client will never use the cache for this value. See
https://www.apollographql.com/docs/react/essentials/local-state/#forcing-resolvers-with-clientalways-true

directives.name: export
directives.description:
Export this locally resolved field as a variable to be used in the remainder of this query. See
https://www.apollographql.com/docs/react/essentials/local-state/#using-client-fields-as-variables

args.name: as
args.description: The variable name to export this field as.

directives.name: connection
directives.description:
Specify a custom store key for this result. See
https://www.apollographql.com/docs/react/advanced/caching/#the-connection-directive

args.name: key
args.description: Specify the store key.

args.name: filter
args.description: An array of query argument names to include in the generated custom store key.
